Elizabeth Riese 20660232 - ENVS 105 Term Paper
Is it desirable or even possible to protect biodiversity while also respecting the interests of
individual organisms? If so, how? If not, why not? Your answer should refer to at least two
of Ian Whyte’s ‘The Elephant Management Dilemma’, Mark Sagoff’s ‘Animal Liberation
and Environmental Ethics’, and Peter Singer’s ‘All Animals are Equal’.
I do believe it is possible and desirable to protect biodiversity while respecting the
interests of individual organisms. One example of conflict between the protection of
biodiversity and individual organisms is the case study brought up by Ian Whyte in his article
‘The Elephant Management Dilemma’. In this article he explains that elephant populations in
Kruger National Park South Africa have led to a large decline in biodiversity due to the
elephants being able to eat an eclectic range of flora, which essentially destroys the habitats
for animals in that area. This leads to the flora and fauna being unable to survive, and
eventually the elephants themselves when all their food sources are gone. The solution posed
by Whyte is to hunt elephants in the academically calculated quantities in order to keep their
population low so that these environments and their inhabitants may flourish. Here the
biodiversity of the South African national park is being protected, but by acting against the
interests of the elephants who, to the best of our knowledge, do not want to be killed.
Although it initially may appear as a dichotomous argument between killing the
elephants and not killing them, there are actually more aspects that come into play. A solution
posed by researcher Allan Savory has proven to be very successful in terms of dealing with
desertification. This solution allows for the protection of biodiversity while also taking into
account the interests of the elephants. Whyte argued that the elephant population is what
caused the destruction of these habitats. Savory originally came to the same conclusion in the

early stages of his research into desertification in similar regions; elephants within South and
East Africa should be killed in order to control their population and thus the biodiversity of
the landscape. Decades after this, he found that population control was not successful in
managing biodiversity nor reversing desertification. He found through his research that
planning, managing, and timing the ranging of large herds of livestock animals (cattle, goats
etc.) with the appropriate drought and wet seasons can restore the flora and fauna of these
habitats within a few years. This is because the defecation of these animals timed with them
pressing it into the ground via their grazing creates an optimum environment for rainwater
capture and soil nutrient balance in wet seasons - therefore, creating an optimum condition
for vegetation to grow. They also trample dead grasses during the drought seasons which
allows grass to decay biologically rather than being burnt by conservationists. When the flora
starts returning to these landscapes, the fauna then returns to these areas which successfully
restores the ecological systems.
1
Rather than killing elephants, conservationists can use this alternative method
proposed by Savory. It is a more complex method, and would require more time and
resources, but it would save the lives of many elephants by doing so. If this method were to
be implemented continuously taking account of the population rate of elephants and the rate
of desertification recovery, then killing them would not be required at all. Sometimes it may
seem like a dichotomous choice between respecting the interests of individual organisms and
the protection of biodiversity, but if there is a possible alternative method as in this case, then
maybe there are other possible methods for other like situations which would satisfy
everyone.

I also do believe it is also desirable to protect biodiversity while respecting the
interests of individual organisms on moral grounds. Peter Singer argues in his article ‘All
Animals are Equal’ that if we truly are a utilitarian society which values the reduction of
suffering for the greatest number, we should take into account the suffering of animals
equally as we do for humans on the principle of equality. Much of the way society runs now
is based off of utilitarianism, and Singer’s argument examines the flaw in the rationality that
the interests of animals should be excluded, or treated less so than that of human beings. In
the case posed by Whyte, this would mean taking into account the interests of the elephants
equally to that of the every being in the ecological system.
One may argue that by killing the elephants we are acting in a utilitarian fashion to
maximize the greatest good for the greatest number, and this may seem like the case to some.
One can examine Whyte’s case study with the deterioration of biodiversity by elephants, and
then reflect on the similar detrimental impact human settlements have on biodiversity for
the sake of their own interests. Humans do not kill each other to protect the biodiversity of
their settlements, let alone even move their settlements to relatively less biodiverse areas
that would feel a lesser impact of human settlement. With Singer’s argument that the
suffering of animals should be considered like that of humans due to the principal of equality,
we cannot deny the elephants their interests to roam and live as they do - similarly to how
humans have their interests equally considered in societies that value the reduction of
suffering in the greatest numbers possible. This may not always be practical in the sense of
biodiversity protection, however if we adhere to the moral principles proposed by Singer we
should desire for respecting the interests of individual organisms, and congruently with the
animals associated with the biodiversity of the ecological system.

One significant criticism of my argument, regarding the balance between protection
of biodiversity and interests of individual organisms being possible and desirable, is the one
posed by Mark Sagoff. In his paper ‘Animal Liberation and Environmental Ethics: Bad Marriage,
Quick Divorce’, Sagoff argues that there is a direct contradiction between these two concepts,
and they therefore both cannot be satisfied. He refers directly to Aldo Leopold’s land ethic,
which aims to promote ecological integrity, and contrasts this with the interest to protect
individual sentient beings. He describes the obligation to protect sentient beings from
suffering as humanitarianism. This concept formed by Sagoff, along with Singer’s similar
argument for reducing the suffering of beings capable of doing so - both from Sagoff’s
perspective appear to be in direct contradiction with Leopold’s land ethic that focuses on
protection of ecological integrity, which in most cases encompasses protection of biodiversity.
Sagoff‘s argument, in the context of the philosophical question posed, is that biodiversity
protection and the interests of individual organisms in general are contradictory and not
compatible. Yet if we again think about Savory’s real life example and experience with his
managed and planned grazing methods, we have a complete and tangible example that is in
opposition to Sagoff’s argument.
Deeply considering their contextual situations and life experiences, philosophers and
researchers such as Whyte and Sagoff have shaped their arguments well all things considered.
It is important to note that there are still new and innovative solutions which arise every day
to old and new problems. With Savory’s example, we know that this is possible to both protect
biodiversity and the interest of individual organisms. Only the case study of elephants in South
and Eastern Africa were discussed in this paper, but it would be interesting to analyze other
examples of conflict between biodiversity and interest of individual organisms to see if a
middle ground could similarly be reached by reflecting on what nature has originally done to
